288
00:15:27,801 --> 00:15:29,837
Spent a lot of time in India.

289
00:15:29,921 --> 00:15:33,630
He wanted to see foreign parts,
he never married.

290
00:15:33,721 --> 00:15:37,157
Then his uncle Tom
was in the Merchant Navy.

291
00:15:38,001 --> 00:15:40,879
Uncle Jim, he was the ne'er-do-well.

292
00:15:40,961 --> 00:15:43,350
When he got married,
I remember Grandad saying:

293
00:15:43,441 --> 00:15:47,832
"He's a nice fella but he'll never be
no good to no woman, not never. "

294
00:15:47,921 --> 00:15:49,957
(Children shout)

295
00:15:57,881 --> 00:16:00,156
(Woman) When I first came here,

296
00:16:00,241 --> 00:16:04,393
we never had none of this lot,
we never had no children in here.

297
00:16:04,481 --> 00:16:07,951
This was only for a married couple

298
00:16:08,041 --> 00:16:11,238
or one on their own, no children.

299
00:16:11,321 --> 00:16:13,437
You had ladies here then.

300
00:16:13,521 --> 00:16:16,035
(Woman) There was rats
under the floorboards.

301
00:16:16,121 --> 00:16:18,635
The council came and put poison down.

302
00:16:18,721 --> 00:16:20,837
They said rats had been there,

303
00:16:20,921 --> 00:16:24,152
but they'd gone somewhere else
to annoy somebody else, like.

304
00:16:24,241 --> 00:16:26,277
(Girl) Reg, we've a new girl at work.

305
00:16:26,361 --> 00:16:28,317
You knew her when you went to school.

306
00:16:28,401 --> 00:16:32,997
- Who's that, then?
- Christine Rowbottom or something.

307
00:16:33,081 --> 00:16:35,356
Oh, I know. Jenkins, weren't it?

308
00:16:35,441 --> 00:16:37,796
That's it. She's on the bra counter.

309
00:16:37,881 --> 00:16:39,837
She's well-suited to that
I'll tell you.

310
00:16:39,921 --> 00:16:41,991
(Laughs)

311
00:16:42,081 --> 00:16:44,436
What happened... wasn't it, erm...

312
00:16:44,521 --> 00:16:46,557
George, remember George?

313
00:16:46,641 --> 00:16:49,201
What, George that had the accident?

314
00:16:49,281 --> 00:16:51,272
Did he have an accident?

315
00:16:51,361 --> 00:16:53,317
Didn't you know? He had his leg off.

316
00:16:53,401 --> 00:16:55,471
Oh, dear, that's terrible.

317
00:16:55,561 --> 00:16:57,870
Very keen on sports, too, I remember.

318
00:16:57,961 --> 00:17:00,555
Lovely little runner, really was.

319
00:17:01,081 --> 00:17:04,551
He won't be able to run any more,
will he?

320
00:17:04,641 --> 00:17:06,711
I don't think it's funny, do you?

321
00:17:06,801 --> 00:17:09,554
(Woman)
It's the only tenement in Islington

322
00:17:09,641 --> 00:17:13,714
where you can sit in your toilet and
cook your breakfast at the same time.

323
00:17:13,801 --> 00:17:18,033
We've only got one bedroom,
I mean, you've got no married life.

324
00:17:18,121 --> 00:17:22,717
Half your questions
and half your rows is over sex,

325
00:17:22,801 --> 00:17:25,315
cos your husbands think
that they've... you know,

326
00:17:25,401 --> 00:17:27,915
and you're always on nerves
with the children.

327
00:17:28,081 --> 00:17:31,517
It's not fair to a man,
or if you're married with children,

328
00:17:31,601 --> 00:17:33,637
I think you're entitled
to have another room.

329
00:17:33,721 --> 00:17:36,519
You can look out your door
up the other woman's passage.

330
00:17:36,601 --> 00:17:38,319
You can't do that in any new flats.

331
00:17:38,401 --> 00:17:41,757
I gave Reg some of those
frozen chips last week.

332
00:17:41,841 --> 00:17:45,959
- He didn't like them much.
- Know what I think about them?

333
00:17:46,041 --> 00:17:48,680
Know what Mr Ward used to say?
Most unhealthy.

334
00:17:48,761 --> 00:17:53,039
(Woman) We make one another a cup
of tea, sit outside and have a laugh.

335
00:17:53,121 --> 00:17:56,591
(Old woman) Keep yourself to
yourself and you can't get in no row.

336
00:17:56,681 --> 00:18:00,833
Cook your dinner now, dear, then I'll
cook ours for Eileen and the boys.

337
00:18:00,921 --> 00:18:03,116
No, I'm gonna put the baby to bed.

338
00:18:03,201 --> 00:18:05,669
It don't work if we have it together.

339
00:18:07,921 --> 00:18:10,116
I'll clear up after him this time.

340
00:18:10,201 --> 00:18:13,273
I think it's a bit hard the council
won't do nothing for you.

341
00:18:13,361 --> 00:18:16,512
I've done my bit,
I've brought up five children.

342
00:18:16,601 --> 00:18:19,274
(Woman) If we could pick,
none of us'd live here.

343
00:18:19,361 --> 00:18:22,353
Stop your fella putting his feet
on the furniture

344
00:18:22,441 --> 00:18:25,160
and picking up the baby
with his filthy hands.

345
00:18:25,241 --> 00:18:28,677
- He's your son!
- But you taught him dirty habits.

346
00:18:28,761 --> 00:18:33,312
Dirty habits? You don't wash your
hands before you touch the baby.

347
00:18:33,401 --> 00:18:36,757
- I was only doing it to help.
- And don't put Daz in his bottle!

348
00:18:36,841 --> 00:18:41,119
- And then there's the toilet.
- What about the sodding toilet?

349
00:18:41,201 --> 00:18:44,557
You know what I mean,
I think it's disgusting!

350
00:18:44,641 --> 00:18:47,474
- Well, of all the meanest things!
- (Baby cries)

351
00:18:47,561 --> 00:18:51,554
You got on my boy's nerves with worry
so that he ran off the road!

352
00:18:51,641 --> 00:18:54,235
- It's about time you was going.
- All right, we'll go.

353
00:18:55,281 --> 00:18:59,718
Keep your rotten old flat, it's
driving me round the bloody bend!

354
00:19:00,561 --> 00:19:02,517
(Children chatter)

355
00:19:02,601 --> 00:19:04,557
(Child) Come 'ere!

356
00:19:06,681 --> 00:19:08,717
Is that your cup of tea?

357
00:19:17,921 --> 00:19:19,912
Say "See you after dinner. "

358
00:19:20,001 --> 00:19:22,196
You're not very friendly, are you?

359
00:19:22,281 --> 00:19:25,159
(Cathy) We moved right away
from the parts we'd been living in.

360
00:19:25,241 --> 00:19:27,516
Reg found quite a good job, too.

361
00:19:27,601 --> 00:19:29,557
We soon fitted in.

362
00:19:29,641 --> 00:19:31,597
Then Stevie came along.

363
00:19:31,681 --> 00:19:33,876
And we got quite settled, really.

364
00:19:33,961 --> 00:19:36,998
These streets looked rough
and there were rats.

365
00:19:37,081 --> 00:19:39,037
But life was quite good here.

366
00:19:39,121 --> 00:19:43,034
Some places were boarded up
with the upstairs windows empty.

367
00:19:43,121 --> 00:19:46,796
Others were crammed full
with people and kiddies.

368
00:19:46,881 --> 00:19:50,112
Once I heard sounds coming
from one of the boarded-up houses.

369
00:19:50,201 --> 00:19:52,556
It sounded like a baby crying.

370
00:19:52,641 --> 00:19:54,871
- Stevie...
- (Squawks)

371
00:19:54,961 --> 00:19:57,555
(Midlands man) I went to a house
the other week.

372
00:19:57,641 --> 00:20:00,599
Woman come out...
it's not too good, I tell you...

373
00:20:00,681 --> 00:20:04,390
.. and she come out
in her knickers and bras.

374
00:20:04,961 --> 00:20:06,872
That's the sort of people I meet.

375
00:20:06,961 --> 00:20:10,271
(Old man) The women used to scrub
the pavements every morning

376
00:20:10,361 --> 00:20:12,317
to keep 'em clean.

377
00:20:12,401 --> 00:20:15,757
(Woman) Me sister came to see me
last week from Yardley.

378
00:20:15,841 --> 00:20:17,832
When she seen the street, she said

379
00:20:17,921 --> 00:20:21,311
"My godfathers, whatever possessed
you to live in a street like this?"

380
00:20:21,401 --> 00:20:24,757
(Man) You knew everybody
and everybody was friendly, like.

381
00:20:24,841 --> 00:20:28,356
But you don't know anybody now and
they're a different class altogether.

382
00:20:28,441 --> 00:20:32,992
(Woman) You'll meet friends in here
and they're very, very nice friends.

383
00:20:33,081 --> 00:20:35,276
You can have a laugh and a joke.

384
00:20:35,361 --> 00:20:39,593
I might have me funny ways, but
I'm a kind-hearted old bit of sugar.

385
00:20:39,681 --> 00:20:45,711
I'm harmless. I'm just an old bag
that has got nobody to turn to.

386
00:20:45,801 --> 00:20:47,792
What happened to Mr Alley, then?

387
00:20:47,881 --> 00:20:51,669
Things have gone too far with these
places, there's too many people.

388
00:20:51,761 --> 00:20:54,753
- The plaster's coming off the walls.
- I hadn't noticed that.

389
00:20:54,841 --> 00:20:58,390
Pull the chain
and half the ceiling comes down.

390
00:20:58,481 --> 00:21:00,437
It's the bloomin' old cistern.

391
00:21:00,521 --> 00:21:03,638
If there's a queue waiting,
one can't follow the other.

392
00:21:03,721 --> 00:21:08,511
(Woman) I've seen all sorts
of changes, from better to worse.

393
00:21:08,601 --> 00:21:11,957
Everybody had window boxes
when I first come up here.

394
00:21:13,281 --> 00:21:16,876
(Mrs Alley) Now, my dear,
once I had a profession.

395
00:21:16,961 --> 00:21:20,397
- Can you guess what it was?
- (Cathy) Ooh, I don't know.

396
00:21:20,481 --> 00:21:24,520
- I was a whore, dear.
- Ooh, you weren't, Mrs Alley!

397
00:21:24,601 --> 00:21:26,717
A whore.

398
00:21:26,801 --> 00:21:28,837
Long time ago.

399
00:21:28,921 --> 00:21:31,594
But I was lovely then.

400
00:21:31,681 --> 00:21:35,754
Had the fellas wild for me, I did,
when I was a whore.

401
00:21:35,841 --> 00:21:39,800
Oh, I've got something
I want you to do for me.

402
00:21:39,881 --> 00:21:42,873
Will you read this letter
for me, dear?

403
00:21:42,961 --> 00:21:45,031
It's one of me old favourites,

404
00:21:45,121 --> 00:21:48,397
and me eyes are not so good
these days.

405
00:21:52,361 --> 00:21:54,829
Oh, Mrs Alley, it's all about sex!

406
00:21:54,921 --> 00:21:58,231
